This paper deals with the problem of book embeddings of directed acyclic graphs, which is a topic in graph theory and combinatorial optimization. The paper presents both algorithmic and combinatorial results, which suggests that it could be relevant to several sub-categories of computer science. Specifically, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) are likely categories since the paper presents algorithms for testing the existence of book embeddings of planar graphs. cs.GT (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.DM (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) are also possible categories since the paper deals with combinatorial problems related to graph embeddings. Finally, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is a possible category since the paper shows that the problem of testing the existence of book embeddings is NP-complete for certain values of k.
